data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_01
data.value: Trimmed camouflage (1950s) A variation of the PLA (People's Liberation Army) multicolor camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_02
data.value: Two-tone disruptive camouflage (late 1940s through 1950s) Early camouflage type introduced by the PLA.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_03
data.value: Two-tone winter camouflage (late 1940s through early 1950s) White stripes on the standard background.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_04
data.value: Dark disruptive camouflage (1950s) Early camouflage type introduced by the PLA.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_07
data.value: Light disruptive camouflage (from mid-1950s) Late type of the PLA two-tone camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_05
data.value: Late three-tone camouflage (until late 1980s) The PLA's basic three-tone camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_06
data.value: Early multicolor camouflage (from mid-1950s) Black spots and light-colored stripes on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_08
data.value: "Large spots" camouflage (late 1960s to present) Still in use.

data.name: camouflage/france/bicolor/franch_1
data.value: Early two-tone camouflage (1918 through 1940) Used during World War I and the interwar period, until the invasion of France.

data.name: camouflage/france/bicolor/franch_4
data.value: Late two-tone camouflage (1930s) Used until the invasion of France.

data.name: camouflage/france/bicolor/franch_5
data.value: Winter camouflage (fall 1925) The French did not have original winter patterns. However, in South Africa they used light grey stripes on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_2
data.value: Trimmed camouflage (1939) Spots with a black-colored braid. A scheme without separating lines was adopted in 1940.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_3
data.value: Late trimmed camouflage (late 1930s through early 1940s) The pattern with braids existed until 1940.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_6
data.value: Three-tone camouflage (1918 through 1920) The camouflage was used during World War I and the post-war period.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_7
data.value: Early diagonal camouflage (1918 through 1920) The camouflage was used during World War I and the post-war period.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_8
data.value: Three-tone disruptive camouflage (1918 through 1920s) The camouflage was used during World War I and the post-war period.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Feldgrau
data.value: Pre-war camouflage (1935 through 1940) Brown stripes on the basic dark grey background. However, from 1940 only the dark grey pattern was used.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/GrayZigzag
data.value: Early desert camouflage (1941 through 1942) Light yellow-brown paint on a dark grey background. The background bled through the paint in the form of spots or stripes.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/RedClouds
data.value: Camouflage "Spots" (1943 through 1944) Brown spots on the basic light yellow-brown background. Used on all fronts.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/WhiteDiagonal
data.value: Winter two-tone camouflage (winter 1941 through 1943) White paint on a dark grey background. Used on the Eastern Front.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/YellowBacillus
data.value: Yellow-brown camouflage "Stripes and spots" (1943 through 1945) A variation of the camouflage with brown stripes and spots on the yellow background.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Honeycomb
data.value: "Large spots" three-tone camouflage (1944) Brown spots with grey trim on the basic background. At the end of the war, due to the shortage of gasoline, dry pigments were mixed with water instead of gasoline, making the background more pale and transparent.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/SnowOnBands
data.value: Multicolor light zebra camouflage (1944 through 1945) It was also called "ambush" camouflage and was used on all fronts.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/SnowOnSpots
data.value: Multicolor dark disruptive camouflage (1944 through 1945) It was also called "ambush" camouflage and was used on all fronts.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/LRDG
data.value: LRDG camouflage (1941 through 1942) A pattern used by the Long Range Desert Group.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/bicolor_classic
data.value: Two-tone plain camouflage (1941 through 1943) Used by the 22nd Tank Brigade regiments.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/desert_splintered
data.value: "Splinter pattern" camouflage (1941 through 1943) Brown spots on the basic background split the vehicle silhouette into separate polygons.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/grassy_green
data.value: Forest green camouflage (1940) Used in Europe.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/sophisticated_bicolor
data.value: Striped camouflage (1941) Used in the U.K.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/tricolor_canadian
data.value: Canadian camouflage (1942) Used by the 1st Canadian Army Tank Brigade in the Dieppe Raid.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/tricolor_classic
data.value: Three-tone universal camouflage (1942 through 1945) Used during the closing stage of World War II.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/tricolor_diagonal
data.value: "Stripes" camouflage (1942) Based on the dazzle pattern accepted by the Navy. Used in North Africa.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/BretagneSky
data.value: Winter camouflage (1941 through 1945) Initially, a variety of white substances were used, including chalk, lime and even salt. The dark olive background color took the form of stripes and spots.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/GuamBicolor
data.value: Tropical two-tone camouflage (1942 through 1945) Used at the Pacific Theatre of operations, in particular on Guam and Okinawa.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/IvozimaBicolor
data.value: Desert two-tone camouflage (1943 through 1945) Used in North Africa and Sicily, as well as in the Pacific Theatre of operations, in particular on Iwo Jima.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/Membane
data.value: "Zigzag" camouflage (1943 through 1944) Used in Italy and Sicily. Dirty yellow stripes on a dark olive background.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/WhiteScar
data.value: "Stripe" camouflage (February 1944) Used by the 4th Marine Regiment in the Pacific Theatre.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/IvozimaTricolor
data.value: Tropical multicolor camouflage (February 1944) Used on Iwo Jima and in other combat operations in the Pacific Theatre.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/OldschoolUsa
data.value: Early camouflage (1917 through 1918) A French camouflage pattern, adopted by U.S. units during World War I.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/RudesheimTricolor
data.value: European three-tone camouflage (1944 through 1945) Often applied over all the equipment and spare parts carried on the vehicle.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/BrownStains
data.value: Summer two-tone camouflage (1944 through 1945) Used by the 334th Heavy SPG Regiment. Brown stripes on a dark green background.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Katukov
data.value: "Katukovsky" winter camouflage (winter 1941 through 1942) Used in the 1st Guards Brigade. Though the pattern is associated with one particular brigade, it was actually based on the pre-war standard winter camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/SpringGhost
data.value: Spring camouflage (April 1942) Lime was applied on the green background and then smeared to achieve different degrees of transparency.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/GasolinePellicle
data.value: Summer three-tone camouflage (1942) Used by the units based near Leningrad. Brown stripes applied on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/Leningrad
data.value: "Large spots" camouflage (August 1939) Commonly used by units based in the western regions of the Soviet Union.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/OldschoolRkka
data.value: Three-tone "large spots" camouflage (1941 through 1942) Used by the 1st Tank Division in Karelia.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/Talvisota
data.value: "Geometrical" three-tone camouflage (1941 through 1942) Used by the 1st tank division in Karelia.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/TricolorZebra
data.value: "Diagonal" camouflage (June through July 1941) Applied in accordance with pre-war requirements. It proved ineffective and was withdrawn.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_13
data.value: Two-tone disruptive camouflage (1980s) A scheme used in the south of China in spring and fall.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_07
data.value: Light disruptive camouflage (from mid-1950s) Late variant of the PLA's two-tone camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_09
data.value: Three-tone camouflage (from 1980s) Used in the north of China, especially in summer.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_10
data.value: Three-tone camouflage (from 1990s) Used in the north-east of China, especially in summer.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_11
data.value: Three-tone desert camouflage Green stripes of different toning on the yellow background. Used by the PLA until the beginning of the 21st century.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_12
data.value: Three-tone camouflage (from 1980s) Used in the south of China, especially in summer.

data.name: camouflage/china/tricolor/china_historical_14
data.value: Three-tone digital camouflage Geometric colored spots divide a vehicle silhouette into fragments. Still in use.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_9
data.value: Brown spots with black braid on the green background (1939) Another variant of the basic pre-war camouflage. In 1940, a scheme without braid was adopted.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Branch
data.value: Three-tone camouflage "Threads" (1944) Brown and dark-green stripes on the basic background. The scheme was widely used by German divisions towards the end of World War II.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Ragged_Patches
data.value: Three-tone "large spots" camouflage (1944 through 1945) Dark-green and brown spots on the basic background. The scheme was used on the Western Front.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/stains_with_notches
data.value: "Trimmed spots" camouflage (1941 through 1943) Large brown spots with double black-and-white trim on a yellow backround. Used in North Africa.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/Tri-color_Spotted
data.value: Tropical three-tone camouflage. Yellow-green and brown paint on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/four-color_stains
data.value: Four-tone early camouflage. The scheme was developed in 1939. Brown, yellow and light-brown paint on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_10
data.value: Three-tone trimmed camouflage (1939 through 1940) Used during the pre-war period and the first years of World War II.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Spots
data.value: Three-tone field camouflage (1944) Small green and brown spots on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/large-spotted
data.value: Desert combined camouflage (1941 through 1943) Used during the North African Campaign.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/Tropical_tricolor
data.value: Tropical three-tone camouflage (1943 through 1945) Used in the Pacific Theatre.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Branches
data.value: "Tree branches" camouflage (1944) Used in the 6th Tank Army.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_desert
data.value: Multicolor desert camouflage (from late 1980s) Late dazzle patterned camouflage type for desert regions.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_winter_1
data.value: Winter white camouflage (late 1940s through late 1950s) A vehicle was painted white with lime or other dye.

data.name: camouflage/china/bicolor/china_historical_winter_2
data.value: Two-tone winter camouflage (1950s through 1960s) White paint was applied in such manner that the background color took the form of stripes and spots.

data.name: camouflage/france/bicolor/Winter
data.value: Winter white camouflage Winter pattern was applied to captured French vehicles fought with the Axis armored forces on the Eastern front.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Winter
data.value: Winter white camouflage As white dry paint was not produced in Germany, all kinds of white dyes were used instead. There were no rules or regulations how to apply winter camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/large-Mickey_Mouse_ears
data.value: Winter white camouflage (winter 1944 through 1945) Paint spots on the white background.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/winter
data.value: Winter white camouflage (winter 1944 through 1945) All kinds of white dyes were in use. There were no rules or regulations how to apply winter camouflage. Every crew made their own choice.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/Winter
data.value: Winter white camouflage (winter 1944 through 1945) All kinds of white dyes were in use. There were no rules or regulations how to apply winter camouflage. Every crew made their own choice.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Winter
data.value: Winter white camouflage White lime or other white dye were applied to the standard background in one or more layers. The pattern was used during World War II.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/Branches_and_Leaves
data.value: "Green grove" (spring through summer 1940) Experimental camouflage. Used by the 8th Tank Battalion.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/Geometric_Shapes
data.value: Two-tone black-striped fragment camouflage (1919) An early camouflage of the French armored forces.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/Gyrus
data.value: Three-tone camouflage with wide intertwining strips (1999) Camouflage of the French peacekeeping forces.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Dark_Spots

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Diagonal_Stripes

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Band
data.value: Three-tone "large spots" camouflage (late 1950s) Used by the South-West Special Military Force.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Brown_Spots
data.value: Three-tone disruptive camouflage. Widely used in the summer of 1941.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/White_Spots
data.value: Two-tone "small spots" camouflage. Widely used from 1941 through 1945.

data.name: camouflage/japan/desert_blue-brown
data.value: Imperial Navy camouflage (from 1930s) Grey-blue aquamarine dye was applied on amphibious vehicles of the Imperial Navy. To improve camouflage, irregularly shaped spots and stripes were applied, in colors depending on the area of operations — in this case, ochre.

data.name: camouflage/japan/desert_green-brown_spots
data.value: Three-tone disruptive camouflage (1930s and from 1945) Green and brown spots applied on khaki-colored background. From 1945 light green was used instead of khaki. The first camouflage pattern is still in use.

data.name: camouflage/japan/summer_four-color
data.value: Three-tone trimmed camouflage (1930s through 1942) Brown-green-yellow camouflage with black or brown trim. Later, yellow color was discontinued. However, the pattern was used in China and Manchuria until 1945.

data.name: camouflage/japan/summer_three-color_spots
data.value: Three-tone mountain camouflage (1940s) Used in the mountainous areas of China.

data.name: camouflage/japan/winter_spots
data.value: White disruptive camouflage (from 1945) White spots on the basic background. Nowadays, spots of regular shapes and various sizes are applied.

data.name: camouflage/japan/winter_white
data.value: “Off-white” camouflage (1942 through 1945) In North China, vehicles were painted white. The dye was rubbed on standard summer camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_Ch_Desert
data.value: Chinese variant of the Flecktarn pattern (from 2003) Used by the frontier forces in Tibet and on the Chinese-Russian border.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_Ch_Summer
data.value: Summer universal Type 07 camouflage (from 2007) Chinese variant of a digital pattern used by the PLA.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_Ch_Winter

data.name: camouflage/IGR_Summer
data.value: Summer camouflage of the Marines of the Republic of Korea (from mid-1970s through early 1980s) The "puzzle" pattern was used.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_Winter
data.value: Winter camouflage of the Naval Landing Forces of the Republic of Korea (from February 2013) First used during combined training with American forces.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_K_Desert
data.value: Desert camouflage (2004) Developed in the Republic of Korea by replacing the colors of the summer camouflage. Used by Korean forces in Afghanistan.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_K_Summer
data.value: Camouflage unofficially designated as “swirl”, “spaghetti”, or “waves” (late 1960s through late 1980s) Used by the special operations forces of the Republic of Korea.

data.name: camouflage/IGR_K_Winter
data.value: Winter variant of “tortoise shell” camouflage pattern (1980s) Used by the Republic of Korea Marine Corps.

data.value: African desert camouflage (1942) Adopted after the introduction of new color pattern standards in Germany. Used by German land forces operating in the North African theater. Uneven sand-colored and gray spots applied over a yellow-brown basic layer.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_6/description
data.value: (1918 through 1920) The camouflage was used during World War I and the post-war period.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_7/description
data.value: (1918 through 1920) The camouflage was used during World War I and the early post-war period.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_8/description
data.value: (1918 through 1920) The camouflage was used during World War I and the early post-war period.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_9/description
data.value: (1939) Another variant of the basic pre-war camouflage. In 1940, a scheme without braid was adopted.

data.name: camouflage/france/tricolor/franch_9/label
data.value: Brown spots with black braid on the green background

data.name: camouflage/germany/DesertTiger/description
data.value: (1942) Adopted after the introduction of new color pattern standards in Germany. Used by German land forces operating in the North African theater. Uneven sand-colored and gray spots applied over a yellow-brown basic layer.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Dark_Spots/description
data.value: (July 1943) Used by the 19th Tank Division during Operation Citadel on the Eastern Front.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Diagonal_Stripes/description
data.value: (spring through summer 1944) Used by armored units during the Normandy Campaign.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Feldgrau/description
data.value: (1935 through 1940) Brown stripes on the basic dark grey background. However, from 1940 only the dark grey pattern was used.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/GrayZigzag/description
data.value: (1941 through 1942) Light yellow-brown paint on a dark grey background. The background bled through the paint in the form of spots or stripes.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Polylines/description
data.value: (summer 1944) Used by the 3d Wehrmacht Tank Army in Lithuania.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/RedClouds/description
data.value: (1943 through 1944) Brown spots on the basic light yellow-brown background. Used on all fronts.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/WhiteDiagonal/description
data.value: (winter 1941 through 1943) White paint on a dark grey background. Used on the Eastern Front.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/Winter/description
data.value: As white dry paint was not produced in Germany, all kinds of white dyes were used instead. There were no rules or regulations how to apply winter camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/germany/bicolor/YellowBacillus/description
data.value: (1943 through 1945) A variation of the camouflage with brown stripes and spots on the yellow background.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Branch/description
data.value: (1944) Brown and dark-green stripes on the basic background. The scheme was widely used by German divisions towards the end of World War II.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Honeycomb/description
data.value: (1944) Brown spots with grey trim on the basic background. At the end of the war, due to the shortage of gasoline, dry pigments were mixed with water instead of gasoline, making the background more pale and transparent.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Ragged_Patches/description
data.value: (1944 through 1945) Dark-green and brown spots on the basic background. The scheme was used on the Western Front.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/SnowOnBands/description
data.value: (1944 through 1945) It was also called "ambush" camouflage and was used on all fronts.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/SnowOnSpots/description
data.value: (1944 through 1945) It was also called "ambush" camouflage and was used on all fronts.

data.name: camouflage/germany/tricolor/Spots/description
data.value: (1944) Small green and brown spots on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/japan/desert_blue-brown/description
data.value: (from 1930s) Grey-blue aquamarine dye was applied on amphibious vehicles of the Imperial Navy. To improve camouflage, irregularly shaped spots and stripes were applied, in colors depending on the area of operations — in this case, ochre.

data.name: camouflage/japan/desert_green-brown_spots/description
data.value: (1930s and from 1945) Green and brown spots applied on khaki-colored background. From 1945 light green was used instead of khaki. The first camouflage pattern is still in use.

data.name: camouflage/japan/summer_four-color/description
data.value: (1930s through 1942) Brown-green-yellow camouflage with black or brown trim. Later, yellow color was discontinued. However, the pattern was used in China and Manchuria until 1945.

data.name: camouflage/japan/summer_three-color_spots/description
data.value: (1940s) Used in the mountainous areas of China.

data.name: camouflage/japan/winter_spots/description
data.value: (from 1945) White spots on the basic background. Nowadays, spots of regular shapes and various sizes are applied.

data.name: camouflage/japan/winter_white/description
data.value: (1942 through 1945) In North China, vehicles were painted white. The dye was rubbed on standard summer camouflage.

data.value: Can be applied to Chinese vehicles

data.value: Can be applied to German vehicles

data.value: Can be applied to Japanese vehicles

data.value: Can be applied to U.K. vehicles

data.value: Can be applied to U.S.S.R. vehicles

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/LRDG/description
data.value: (1941 through 1942) A pattern used by the Long Range Desert Group.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/bicolor_classic/description
data.value: (1941 through 1943) Used by the 22nd Tank Brigade regiments.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/desert_splintered/description
data.value: (1941 through 1943) Brown spots on the basic background split the vehicle silhouette into separate polygons.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/large-Mickey_Mouse_ears/description
data.value: (winter 1944 through 1945) Paint spots on the white background.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/winter/description
data.value: (winter 1944 through 1945) All kinds of white dyes were in use. There were no rules or regulations how to apply winter camouflage. Every crew made their own choice.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/large-spotted/description
data.value: (1941 through 1943) Used during the North African Campaign.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/stains_with_notches/description
data.value: (1941 through 1943) Large brown spots with double black-and-white trim on a yellow backround. Used in North Africa.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/tricolor_canadian/description
data.value: (1942) Used by the 1st Canadian Army Tank Brigade in the Dieppe Raid.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/tricolor_classic/description
data.value: (1942 through 1945) Used during the closing stage of World War II.

data.name: camouflage/uk/tricolor/tricolor_diagonal/description
data.value: (1942) Based on the dazzle pattern accepted by the Navy. Used in North Africa.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/BretagneSky/description
data.value: (1941 through 1945) Initially, a variety of white substances were used, including chalk, lime and even salt. The dark olive background color took the form of stripes and spots.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/GuamBicolor/description
data.value: (1942 through 1945) Used at the Pacific Theatre of operations, in particular on Guam and Okinawa.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/IvozimaBicolor/description
data.value: (1943 through 1945) Used in North Africa and Sicily, as well as in the Pacific Theatre of operations, in particular on Iwo Jima.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/Membane/description
data.value: (1943 through 1944) Used in Italy and Sicily. Dirty yellow stripes on a dark olive background.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/WhiteScar/description
data.value: (February 1944) Used by the 4th Marine Regiment in the Pacific Theatre.

data.name: camouflage/usa/bicolor/Winter/description
data.value: (winter 1944 through 1945) All kinds of white dyes were in use. There were no rules or regulations how to apply winter camouflage. Every crew made their own choice.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/IvozimaTricolor/description
data.value: (February 1944) Used on Iwo Jima and in other combat operations in the Pacific Theatre.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/OldschoolUsa/description
data.value: (1917 through 1918) A French camouflage pattern, adopted by U.S. units during World War I.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/RudesheimTricolor/description
data.value: (1944 through 1945) Often applied over all the equipment and spare parts carried on the vehicle.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/Tri-color_Spotted/description
data.value: Yellow-green and brown paint on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/Tropical_tricolor/description
data.value: (1943 through 1945) Used in the Pacific Theatre.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Band/description
data.value: (late 1950s) Used by the South-West Special Military Force.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/BrownStains/description
data.value: (1944 through 1945) Used by the 334th Heavy SPG Regiment. Brown stripes on a dark green background.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Brown_Spots/description
data.value: Widely used in the summer of 1941.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Katukov/description
data.value: (winter 1941 through 1942) Used in the 1st Guards Brigade. Though the pattern is associated with one particular brigade, it was actually based on the pre-war standard winter camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/SpringGhost/description
data.value: (April 1942) Lime was applied on the green background and then smeared to achieve different degrees of transparency.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/bicolor/Winter/description
data.value: White lime or other white dye were applied to the standard background in one or more layers. The pattern was used during World War II.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/GasolinePellicle/description
data.value: (1942) Used by the units based near Leningrad. Brown stripes applied on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/Leningrad/description
data.value: (August 1939) Commonly used by units based in the western regions of the Soviet Union.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/OldschoolRkka/description
data.value: (1941 through 1942) Used by the 1st Tank Division in Karelia.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/Talvisota/description
data.value: (1941 through 1942) Used by the 1st tank division in Karelia.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/TricolorZebra/description
data.value: (June through July 1941) Applied in accordance with pre-war requirements. It proved ineffective and was withdrawn.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/tricolor/four-color_stains/description
data.value: The scheme was developed in 1939. Brown, yellow and light-brown paint on the basic background.

data.name: camouflage/Clan_camouflage_02/description
data.value: U.S.S.R. winter two-tone "large spots" camouflage (January 1945) Used in East Prussia.

data.name: camouflage/Clan_camouflage_03/description
data.value: U.S.S.R. summer two-tone "large spots" camouflage (1920) Used in Russia.

data.name: camouflage/Clan_camouflage_04/description
data.value: Chinese summer four-tone camouflage The so-called “pixel” camouflage used in the early 2010s.

data.name: emblem/group10/special_21
data.value: Best Replays of the Week Emblem

data.name: inscription/clan_content/inscription_21
data.value: What is essential in war is victory, not prolonged operations.

data.name: camouflage/usa/tricolor/usa_premium_asia/description
data.value: Used by the Armored Forces of the Taiwan Marine Corps.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/fallout_camo_Object_730/description
data.value: A variant of camouflage made with standard 7K paint and used in open-terrain locations (roads, steppes, farmland). The following items are additionally included with the camouflage: • Guardian Emblem—an Emblem that was applied to vehicles of Guards units of the Red Army and, later, to vehicles of other units • Elephant—the tactical insignia of the 14th Guards Mechanized Brigade • Tactical Vehicle Number Awarded to players who achieved impressive results during battles on the Global Map.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/fallout_camo_Object_907/description
data.value: A variant of camouflage made with standard 7K paint and used in open-terrain locations (roads, steppes, farmland). The following items are additionally included with the camouflage: • Guardian Emblem—an Emblem that was applied to vehicles of Guards units of the Red Army and, later, to vehicles of other units • Bear—the tactical insignia of the 36th Guards Tank Bridage • Tactical Vehicle Number

data.name: camouflage/Cracked_ice/description
data.value: A camouflage pattern that resembles tree branches in a deciduous forest in winter. Disrupts the vehicle’s silhouette, making the vehicle significantly less noticeable. Highly effective for ambush tactics. Applied in the field using washable white, or chalk and lime paint.

data.name: camouflage/Desert_camou/description
data.value: A camouflage pattern used in rocky areas with thick layers of sand. Significantly disrupts the vehicle’s silhouette at medium and long range, by imitating the misshapen shadows from uneven terrain on the hull. Applied using yellowish-grey and greenish-brown paints.

data.name: camouflage/czech/Cz_dust/description
data.value: Used in the summer of 1942. A desert camouflage did not exist in the Czechoslovakian army until 1939. Yellow spots were applied over the primary grey color of Czechoslovakian vehicles in the 22nd Panzer Division.

data.name: camouflage/czech/Cz_summer/description
data.value: Used until 1939. Yellow and brown spots up to 100 cm long and 40 cm wide were applied over dull green dye. No strict pattern for applying spots was used. Each vehicle had a unique pattern.

data.name: camouflage/czech/Cz_winter/description
data.value: Used from 1941 through 1942. A winter camouflage did not exist in the Czechoslovakian army until 1939. Czechoslovakian vehicles in the 8th Panzer Division of the Wehrmacht were dabbed with white dye over the primary grey color.

data.name: camouflage/nation/czech
data.value: Can be applied to Czechoslovakian vehicles

data.name: camouflage/summer_camo/description
data.value: Camouflage for marshy and forested areas. Its earth tones and geometry effectively disrupt and hide the vehicle’s silhouette in foliage, and allow it to stay unspotted to ambush enemies.

data.value: Emblem of the Republic of China

data.name: emblem/group4/signs_95
data.value: Emblem of the Canadian Armed Forces

data.name: camouflage/Clan_damaged/description
data.value: This camouflage outlines the heroic past of the long-serving vehicle and features numerous markings from battles: powder spots, chipped paint, and dirt. It uses a basic color palette and is only applied to vehicles awarded for Global Map events.

data.name: camouflage/czech/bicolor/Cz_desert01/description
data.value: A pattern of sand-colored spots applied over a base layer, covering 30 to 40% of a vehicle’s surface. A Czechoslovakian tank with this camouflage, used by the 20th Wehrmacht tank division, was spotted near Demyansk in March of 1942.

data.name: camouflage/czech/bicolor/Cz_winter01/description
data.value: This pattern is applied with a combination of water-emulsion paint and whitewash over a base layer of uneven spots, which covered approximately 50% of a vehicle’s surface. This camouflage was used in the winter of 1941–1942 by the 12th Wehrmacht tank division.

data.name: camouflage/uk/bicolor/australian/description
data.value: (1941 through 1943) Some Sentinel tanks had large-spotted camouflage patterns applied in dark green and bright yellow colors. Most of the Sentinel tanks on display today bear this camouflage pattern.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/Custom_R127_T44_100_P_desert/description
data.value: Вторая половина 50-х гг. Наносился на технику Вооружённых Сил СССР.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/Custom_R127_T44_100_P_summer/description
data.value: Начало 50-х гг. Наносился на технику в составе 1-й гвардейской механизированной дивизии ЗакВО.

data.name: camouflage/ussr/Custom_R127_T44_100_P_winter/description
data.value: 1944 год. Предназначался для техники, участвовавшей в боевых действиях в условиях степи. Отличался от уставного камуфляжа цветом. Не был утверждён из-за сложности нанесения на боевые машины.

data.name: camouflage/Sw_desert_01/description
data.value: (first half of the 1960s) Gravel spots against the base layer. Used in the Congo for Swedish armored vehicles manufactured by Unimog-Landsverk.

data.name: camouflage/Sw_desert_02/description
data.value: Black spots with washed out edges against the base olive-grey layer.

data.name: camouflage/Sw_summer_01/description
data.value: (1920 through 1930) Brown, foliage green, and fallow spots separated by a fine geometric or wavy outline in black or white. Each of the colors occupied approximately 30% of the total area.

data.name: camouflage/Sw_summer_02/description
data.value: (before the 1950s) Nonuniformly shaped spots of black, yellow, green, brown, and various hues of these colors against the grey base layer. Applied with a spray gun to all parts except the sides and suspension, occupying at least 25% of the total vehicle's surface. Used on Swedish armored vehicles.

data.name: camouflage/Sw_winter_01/description
data.value: (from the 1930s) Water-based paint applied with brushes and a spray gun. Used on armored vehicles of the Swedish Armed Forces in winter.

data.name: camouflage/Sw_winter_02/description
data.value: (from the 1930s) Water-based paint applied with brushes. Painted spots alternated with areas of the unpainted base layer. Used on armored vehicles of the Swedish Armed Forces in winter.

data.name: camouflage/nation/sweden
data.value: Can be applied to Swedish vehicles

data.name: camouflage/Splinter_desert/description
data.value: (Late 1940s) French experiments in the development of disruptive camouflage painting had a huge impact on world tank construction. Later, they formed a basis for the camouflage patterns of numerous countries. High-contrasting spots break up the vehicle’s silhouette, making it difficult to aim at.

data.name: camouflage/Splinter_summer/description
data.value: (From 1931) One of the earliest German camouflage patterns, the "Splittermuster", was particularly successful. Different color variations were used by numerous countries, including France.

data.name: camouflage/Splinter_winter/description
data.value: (From 1950s) In the post-war period, combinations of various shades of similar colors, along with the proven "splinter" pattern, were frequently used. A similar principle is used for applying modern "digital" camouflage patterns.

data.name: camouflage/Desert_Tiger_217/description
data.value: This camouflage is typical for vehicles with zimmerit applied due to the presence of ochre in its composition. Zimmerit was actively used by Germany as antimagnetic substance on the Eastern Front from the beginning of 1943 through the fall of 1944.

data.name: camouflage/Tiger217_Summer/description
data.value: Green stripes were applied over the basic yellow color. The camouflage was used by the 502nd Heavy Panzer Battalion in Lithuania in the summer of 1944.

data.name: camouflage/Tiger217_winter/description
data.value: Germany did not produce dry white paint for armored vehicles; therefore, many improvised dyes were used, including lime. The dye was applied over the basic yellow color. There were no particular regulations (and patterns) for applying winter camouflage.

data.name: camouflage/poland/PL_desert_01/description
data.value: Tawny olive two-tone camouflage that was used by the Polish armored units within the British army in Iraq and Africa from 1940 through 1943.

data.name: camouflage/poland/PL_summer_02/description
data.value: Applied to vehicles of Polish units in Britain from 1940 through 1945.

data.name: camouflage/poland/PL_winter_01/description
data.value: Used before WWII during training exercises. Vehicles were painted with a washable solution (most likely, whitewash). There are no examples of vehicles with such camouflage in 1939, as the 1939 Defensive War in Poland was over by the end of September.

data.name: camouflage/PM_desert_ob260/description
data.value: The Amoeba camouflage pattern consists of brown, white, and black irregular-shaped spots. Designed in the second half of the 1920s and widely used by the Red Army.

data.name: camouflage/PM_desert_stugiv/description
data.value:
A desert variation of the "ambush" camouflage pattern introduced in the late summer–early fall of 1944.
Small free form patches of brownish shades are applied over the light yellow base color.

data.name: camouflage/PM_desert_t28htc/description
data.value:
A desert variation combining two camouflage patterns: Coffee Stain and Chocolate Chip.
The Coffee Stain uniforms were used by the U.S. Armed Forces from 1992 to the early 2010s. The Chocolate Chip uniforms were used by the U.S. Armed Forces from the early 1980s to the mid-1990s.

data.name: camouflage/PM_desert_t55a/description
data.value:
A desert variation of camouflage pattern for wheeled and tracked armored fighting vehicles of GDR Armed Forces, introduced in 1988.
This pattern entailed changing the summer pattern colors to varying colors and shades characteristic of arid environments: light brown, sand, gray sand, etc.

data.name: camouflage/PM_summer_ob260/description
data.value: The Amoeba camouflage pattern consists of irregular-shaped spots of varying shades of green. Designed in the second half of the 1920s and widely used by the Red Army.

data.name: camouflage/PM_summer_stugiv/description
data.value:
A scheme of the "ambush" camouflage pattern introduced in the late summer–early fall of 1944.
Disc-shaped green and brown patches are applied over the dark yellow base color along with additional brown dots between them.

data.name: camouflage/PM_summer_t28htc/description
data.value:
A summer variation combining two camouflage patterns: Coffee Stain and Chocolate Chip.
The Coffee Stain uniforms were used by the U.S. Armed Forces from 1992 to the early 2010s. The Chocolate Chip uniforms were used by the U.S. Armed Forces from the early 1980s to the mid-1990s.

data.name: camouflage/PM_summer_t55a/description
data.value:
A summer camouflage pattern for wheeled and tracked armored combat vehicles of GDR Armed Forces, introduced in 1988.
Large brown and dark green spots-stripes were applied over the base green color.

data.name: camouflage/PM_winter_ob260/description
data.value: The Amoeba camouflage pattern consists of gray, white, and black irregular-shaped spots. Designed in the second half of the 1920s and widely used by the Red Army.

data.name: camouflage/PM_winter_stugiv/description
data.value:
A winter variation of the "ambush" camouflage pattern introduced in the late summer–early fall of 1944.
Small free form patches of white and black colors are applied over the base color. Ideally suited for conducting ambushes in urban warfare.

data.name: camouflage/PM_winter_t28htc/description
data.value:
A winter variation combining two camouflage patterns: Coffee Stain and Chocolate Chip.
The Coffee Stain uniforms were used by the U.S. Armed Forces from 1992 to the early 2010s. The Chocolate Chip uniforms were used by the U.S. Armed Forces from the early 1980s to the mid-1990s.

data.name: camouflage/PM_winter_t55a/description
data.value:
A winter variation of camouflage pattern for wheeled and tracked armored fighting vehicles of GDR Armed Forces, introduced in 1988.
In this variation light gray and black spots were painted over with white color.
